Introduction

Business Context. You are a data scientist working for a machine learning consultancy. One of your clients wants to be able to classify text reviews automatically by the likely rating (on a 1 - 5 scale) that that person would give. However, they do not have sufficient data they generated on their own to do this, so you need to use an external, rich dataset as a basis on which to build your model and then translate it over.

Business Problem. Your task is to build a neural networks-based model for classifying text reviews into likely ratings (on a 1 - 5 scale).

Analytical Context. We'll use the Amazon review dataset again and try to classify reviews into star ratings automatically. Instead of just positive and negative, we'll take on the harder challenge of predicting the exact star rating. The lowest score is 1 and the highest is 5.

Instead of trying to optimize by pre-processing the text, we'll do very basic tokenization and experiment with different neural network models, architectures, and hyperparameters to optimize the results. You'll start by building a simple dense neural network and try to get it to perform better using various techniques. Then you'll evaluate the results and diagnose where it tends to perform more poorly.

Tokenizing our texts

Keras comes with its own functions to preprocess text, including a tokenizer (a mapping from each word in our corpus to a unique integer). Unlike the CountVectorizer from sklearn, which produces sparse matrices, keras often expects to work with sequences representing only the words that occur in a text. To prepare text before feeding it into a neural network, we usually:

  1. Create a tokenizer.
  2. Create sequences from our text (each text becomes a list of integers, based on the tokenizer mapping, instead of words)
  3. Pad or truncate each sequence to a fixed length (very short texts get 0s added to them, while very long ones are truncated).

The tokenizer has a configurable word cap, so it will only consider the $n$ most common words in the corpus, ignoring very rare words.

def plotCountComponents(data, var, ax : int, color, xlab='', main='', xlim=(0,0)):
  sns.histplot(data[var], linewidth=1, alpha = 0.8, color=color, ax=ax, bins=100)
  ax.axvline(data[var].quantile([0.2, 0.8]).iloc[0], ls='--',color = 'black')
  ax.axvline(data[var].quantile([0.2, 0.8]).iloc[1], ls='--',color = 'black')
  ax.set(title=main, xlabel=xlab, xlim=xlim)

def columnwithNgrams(data, n, k, notWords = None, qr='Score!=10'):
  stopWords1 = list(stop_words); stopWords1.extend(notWords)
  df = data.query(qr)
  du = df['Text'].apply(lambda x: nltk.word_tokenize(x))
  du = map(lambda x: [i for i in x if i.lower() not in stopWords1], du)
  du = map(lambda x: [i for i in x if i not in string.punctuation], du)
  du = map(lambda x: [" ".join(i) for i in ngrams(x, n)], du) 
  
  most_common_k = Counter([i for j in du for i in j]).most_common(k)
  most_common_DF = pd.DataFrame({'Gram': dict(most_common_k).keys(), 
                                 'Count':map(int, dict(most_common_k).values())})

  return most_common_DF

Building a basic neural network model

Now that we have preprocessed the text, let's create a basic neural network to train on our data. We'll use an embedding layer which performs one-hot encoding on our word sequences, two fully connected ("dense") layers, and an output layer with 5 neurons to represent the 5 possible star ratings.

Before we train a keras model, there is an additional compile step where we define what loss function and optimizer to use, and what metrics to output. Then we can train the model using the fit function. All of this is shown below.

Note the validation_split=0.2 argument which tells Keras to train on only 80% of the training data and tune the model on the remaining 20%, which we call the validation set. You can see the accuracy and loss for both the training and validation set in the output for each epoch:

In [38]:
model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(20000, 128, input_length=116))
model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model.add(GlobalMaxPooling1D())
model.add(Dense(5, activation='sigmoid'))
model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])

def trainingHistoryPlot(model, title = 'Training History'):
  d = pd.DataFrame(model.history.history).reset_index()
  fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,4))
  sns.lineplot(x = 'index', y = 'loss', data=d, label='loss', ax=ax[0])
  sns.lineplot(x = 'index', y = 'val_loss', data=d, label='val_loss', ax=ax[0])
  sns.lineplot(x = 'index', y = 'accuracy', data=d, label='accuracy', ax=ax[1])
  sns.lineplot(x = 'index', y = 'val_accuracy', data=d, label='val_accuracy', ax=ax[1]);
  ax[0].set(xlabel='Epoch #'); ax[1].set(xlabel='Epoch #');
  fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=18);
  return

trainingHistoryPlot(model, 'Training History - Base Neural Network')

def confusion(ytest, y_pred, title=''):
    names=["Positive","Negative"]
    cm = multilabel_confusion_matrix(ytest, y_pred)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(15,3))
    # ax = ax.ravel()
    for i, mat in enumerate(cm):
      mat1 = mat/np.sum(mat)
      mat_rav = mat.ravel()

      sns.heatmap(mat1, fmt='.1%', annot=True, linewidth=.5, linecolor="black", cmap = 'Blues', ax=ax[i], cbar=False, vmin=0, vmax=1)
      ax[i].set(xlabel=r"$\mathrm{y_{pred}}$", ylabel=r"$\mathrm{y_{true}}$")
      ax[i].set(title = "Score {}".format(i+1))
      ax[i].set_xticklabels(names); ax[i].set_yticklabels(names)
      for r, t in zip(mat_rav, ax[i].texts): t.set_text(t.get_text() + "\n({})".format(r))

    fig.set_tight_layout(True)
    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=15, verticalalignment='bottom')
    
    plt.show()
    return

Experimenting with different regularization strategies

There are many different ways to mitigate overfitting in a neural network, collectively known as regularization techniques. One common regularization technique is called Dropout. In this regularization method, a set of neurons is randomly selected at each training step to be completely ignored. This is done so that the neurons in our network do not rely strongly on their neighboring neurons and we avoid the creation of "co-adaptations" that do not generalize well to unseen data. This making the model more robust and less prone to overffiting.

You can create dropouts in keras by adding a layer named Dropout(p), where p is the probability of dropping neurons in the previous layer. For example, the following model would implement dropout by removing roughly 20% percent of the outputs of the embedding layer at each training step:

def create_model(dropout=0.0):
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Embedding(20000, 128, input_length=116))
  model.add(Dropout(dropout))
  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu')) 
  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
  model.add(GlobalMaxPooling1D())
  model.add(Dense(5, activation='sigmoid'))
  model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

def create_model(l1 = 0.01, l2 = 0.01):
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Embedding(20000, 128, input_length=116))
  model.add(Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', 
                  kernel_regularizer = regularizers.l1_l2(l1=l1, l2=l2), 
                  bias_regularizer=regularizers.l1_l2(l1=l1, l2=l2), 
                  activity_regularizer=regularizers.l1_l2(l1=l1, l2=l2) )) 
  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu',
                  kernel_regularizer = regularizers.l1_l2(l1=l1, l2=l2), 
                  bias_regularizer=regularizers.l1_l2(l1=l1, l2=l2), 
                  activity_regularizer=regularizers.l1_l2(l1=l1, l2=l2) ))
  model.add(GlobalMaxPooling1D())
  model.add(Dense(5, activation='sigmoid'))
  model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

def create_model(l2 = 0.01):
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Embedding(20000, 128, input_length=116))
  model.add(Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', 
                  kernel_regularizer = regularizers.l2(l2), 
                  bias_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2), 
                  activity_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2) )) 
  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu',
                  kernel_regularizer = regularizers.l2(l2), 
                  bias_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2), 
                  activity_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2) ))
  model.add(GlobalMaxPooling1D())
  model.add(Dense(5, activation='sigmoid'))
  model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

In this case, it is observed that the L2 regularization (applied all together in the kernel, bias and activity) has a deleterious effect on the precision of the model, if the parameter $\lambda_2$ has a value greater than $10^{-4}$, underfitting begins to be observed, and when increasing by more than $10^{-3}$ it is observed that there is overfitting.

For the reasons mentioned above, it is decided to use a value $\lambda_{2} $ of $10^{- 4} $ to prevent a bad behavior of the model, below we can see in more detail the behavior of this model.

3. Best sub component to regularize each layer¶

In [83]:
def create_model(inKernel = False, inBias=False, inActivity=False, l2=1e-4):
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Embedding(20000, 128, input_length=116))
  model.add(Dropout(0.2))

  if inKernel is False: kernelRegularizer = 'None'; 
  else: kernelRegularizer = 'regularizers.l2(l2)'
  if inBias is False: biasRegularizer = 'None'
  else: biasRegularizer = 'regularizers.l2(l2)'
  if inActivity is False: activityRegularizer = 'None'
  else: activityRegularizer = 'regularizers.l2(l2)'

  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', 
                  kernel_regularizer   = eval(kernelRegularizer), 
                  bias_regularizer     = eval(biasRegularizer), 
                  activity_regularizer = eval(activityRegularizer) )) 
  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu',
                  kernel_regularizer   = eval(kernelRegularizer), 
                  bias_regularizer     = eval(biasRegularizer), 
                  activity_regularizer = eval(activityRegularizer) )) 
  model.add(GlobalMaxPooling1D())
  model.add(Dense(5, activation='sigmoid'))
  model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
  
  return model

In [11]:
def create_model(both_layers = [True, True], inKernel = False, inBias=False, inActivity=False, l2=1e-4):
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Embedding(20000, 128, input_length=116))
  model.add(Dropout(0.2))

  if inKernel is False: kernelRegularizer = 'None'; 
  else: kernelRegularizer = 'regularizers.l2(l2)'
  if inBias is False: biasRegularizer = 'None'
  else: biasRegularizer = 'regularizers.l2(l2)'
  if inActivity is False: activityRegularizer = 'None'
  else: activityRegularizer = 'regularizers.l2(l2)'

  if both_layers[0] is True:
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu',
                  kernel_regularizer   = eval(kernelRegularizer), 
                  bias_regularizer     = eval(biasRegularizer), 
                  activity_regularizer = eval(activityRegularizer) )) 
  else:
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))

  if both_layers[1] is True:
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu',
                  kernel_regularizer   = eval(kernelRegularizer), 
                  bias_regularizer     = eval(biasRegularizer), 
                  activity_regularizer = eval(activityRegularizer) )) 
  else:
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
  
  model.add(GlobalMaxPooling1D())
  model.add(Dense(5, activation='sigmoid'))
  model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
  
  return model

This result suggests that regularization should not be used in the deep layers of the neural network, because the base model shows better precision for the training and validation data.

Regularization through adding more data

Depending on the configurations you tried above, you probably saw that L1 and L2 regularization are pretty limited for this model and this amount of data. A more straightforward way to prevent overfitting is simply by adding more training data. If the network has more (and more varied) examples to learn from, perhaps it will learn more generalizable rules.

Regularization through early stopping

We have consistently seen that our neural network overfits at around the third epoch. Hence, another form of regularization is to end training early if validation loss starts increasing. (This is similar to the validation curves we used when constructing classification models.) Although the network will not have found an optimal function in the training data, the looser function that it has found will likely be more generalizable.

You can do this manually by inspecting the data as we have done above and modifying the epochs argument in fit(), but Keras also allows you to easily do this automatically via an EarlyStopping callback.

Evaluating our model

Unlike in most previous cases, we used three splits of our data instead of two. All of our model tuning has been done on the validation set, and we have not even touched the test set that we split off right at the start.

For experiments, it's very important that your model is only run once on your test set. As there is so much randomness at play, it's vital to not "cherry-pick" the best results, so optimize as much as you want on the validation set, but keep the test set until the end and all official results should be based on the single run of the test set (or whatever configuration was decided before the experiment started).

Hopefully, you have seen from this that there is no one-size-fits-all method when creating model architectures or tuning parameters. Often times, copious experimentation is needed, and even then it can be difficult to get significantly better results than a baseline model or even really diagnose what is going wrong under the hood (since neural networks are so "black-box"). In many cases, the quantity and quality of the data itself is far more important than the architecture of the network for getting good results.
